**Navigation & Context (Know where you are)**

1. `pwd` — Print working directory. **Use this constantly.** You must know if you are in `~/Downloads` or `~/Projects` before running any script.
2. `ls -la` — List with hidden files and permissions. The `-a` reveals `.zshrc` and `.venv`; the `-l` shows if you have execute permissions.
3. `cd -` — Jump to previous directory. Essential when you `cd` deep into a project then need to snap back.
4. `mkdir -p path/to/nested/dir` — Create parent directories as needed. You will use this to organize projects before writing code.

**Inspection (Read before you run)**
5. `file filename` — Tells you what type of file something is (text, binary, shell script). 
Prevents you from trying to `cat` an image or executable.
6. `less filename` — Read long files without flooding your terminal. Use `q` to quit, `/` to search.
7. `head -n 20 filename` — Read just the top of a file. Useful for checking Python shebangs or README instructions.

**Environment (Where commands live)**
8. `echo $PATH` — **This is the most important command on your list.** 

It prints the colon-separated list of directories where zsh searches for commands. 
If you install something and get "command not found," it means the binary is in a directory not listed here.

9. `which python3` — Tells you the absolute path of the `python3` binary that would execute if you typed it right now. 
Critical for verifying you are using Homebrew's Python vs. Apple's system Python.
10. `export PATH="/new/directory:$PATH"` — Temporarily adds a directory to your search path for the current session. 
You will use this to fix "command not found" errors before making them permanent in `.zshrc`.

**Python Workflow (The development loop)**
11. `python3 -m venv venv` — Creates a virtual environment named `venv` in the current directory. 
**Never skip this.** It isolates your project dependencies from the system Python.
12. `source venv/bin/activate` — Activates the virtual environment. 
Your prompt will change to show `(venv)`. Now `pip` and `python` point to the isolated versions.
13. `pip install package_name` — Installs Python libraries. 
**Only run this when you see `(venv)` in your prompt.** 
If you use `sudo pip`, you have failed and must uninstall and start over.

**System & Permissions (macOS specific)**
14. `brew install package` — Homebrew is the de facto package manager for macOS. 
You will use this to install `python3`, `git`, and eventually Rust (for NOSTR). 
If you haven't installed Homebrew yet, that is Step Zero.
15. `chmod +x script.py` — Makes a file executable. 
On macOS, you cannot run a script with `./script.py` unless it has the execute bit set (shown as `x` in `ls -l`).

